enheit)%20above%20the%20pre-industrial%20mean.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20would%20be%20at%20least%200.2C%20(0.4F)%20warmer%20than%20July%202019%2C%20the%20former%20front-runner%20in%20the%20174-year%20observational%20record%2C%20according%20to%20European%20Union%20data.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20margin%20of%20difference%20between%20now%20and%20July%202019%20is%20%26quot%3Bso%20substantial%20that%20we%20can%20already%20say%20with%20absolute%20certainty%20that%20it%20is%20going%20to%20be%20the%20warmest%20July%2C%26quot%3B%20Leipzig%20climate%20scientist%20Karsten%20Haustein%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMichael%20Mann%2C%20a%20climate%20scientist%20at%20the%20University%20of%20Pennsylvania%2C%20said%20it%20was%20clear%20by%20mid-July%20that%20it%20was%20going%20to%20be%20a%20record%20warm%20month%2C%20and%20provided%20an%20%26quot%3Bindicator%20of%20a%20planet%20that%20will%20continue%20to%20warm%20as%20long%20as%20we%20burn%20fossil%20fuels%26quot%3B.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ENormally%2C%20the%20global%20mean%20temperature%20for%20July%20is%20around%2016C%20(61F)%2C%20inclusive%20of%20the%20Southern%20Hemisphere%20winter.%20But%20this%20July%20it%20has%20surged%20to%20near%2017C%20(63F).%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhat's%20more%2C%20%26quot%3Bwe%20may%20have%20to%20go%20back%20thousands%20if%20not%20tens%20of%20thousands%20of%20years%20to%20find%20similarly%20warm%20conditions%20on%20our%20planet%2C%26quot%3B%20Haustein%20said.%20Early%2C%20less%20fine-tuned%20climate%20records%20-%20gathered%20from%20things%20like%20ice%20cores%20and%20tree%20rings%20-%20suggest%20the%20Earth%20has%20not%20been%20this%20hot%20in%20120%2C000%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHaustein's%20analysis%20is%20based%20on%20preliminary%20temperature%20data%20and%20weather%20models%2C%20including%20forecast%20temperatures%20through%20the%20end%20of%20this%20month%2C%20but%20validated%20by%20unaffiliated%20scientists.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20U.N.%20World%20Meteorological%20Organization%20(WMO)%20also%20said%20on%20Thursday%20it%20was%20%26quot%3Bextremely%20likely%26quot%3B%20July%202023%20would%20break%20the%20record%2C%20but%20would%20not%20call%20it%20outright%2C%20instead%20waiting%20until%20the%20availability%20of%20all%20finalised%20data.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BJuly%20is%20almost%20certainly%20the%20hottest%20month%20in%20the%20instrumental%20record%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Piers%20Forster%2C%20a%20climate%20scientist%20at%20Leeds%20University%20in%20Britain.%20%26quot%3BThe%20result%20is%20confirmed%20by%20several%20independent%20datasets%20combining%20measurements%20in%20the%20ocean%20and%20over%20land.%20It%20is%20statistically%20robust.%26quot%3B%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EHOTHOUSE%20PLANET%C2%A0%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESweltering%20temperatures%20have%20affected%20considerable%20swathes%20of%20the%20planet.%20While%20night-time%20is%20typically%20cooler%20in%20the%20desert%2C%20Death%20Valley%20in%20the%20U.S.%20state%20of%20California%20saw%20the%20hottest%20night%20ever%20recorded%20globally%20this%20month.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETemperatures%20in%20a%20northwest%20China%20township%20soared%20as%20high%20as%2052.2C%20(126F)%2C%20breaking%20the%20national%20record.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECanadian%20wildfires%20burned%20at%20an%20unprecedented%20pace.%20And%20France%2C%20Spain%2C%20Germany%20and%20Poland%20sizzled%20under%20a%20major%20heatwave%2C%20with%20the%20mercury%20climbing%20into%20the%20mid-40s%20on%20the%20Italian%20island%20of%20Sicily%2C%20part%20of%20which%20is%20engulfed%20in%20flames.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20is%20%26quot%3Bthe%20harsh%20reality%20of%20climate%20change%20and%20a%20foretaste%20of%20the%20future%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20WMO%20Secretary-General%20Petteri%20Taalas.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20ocean%2C%20too%2C%20is%20in%20hot%20water.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMarine%20heatwaves%20have%20unfolded%20along%20coastlines%20from%20Florida%20to%20Australia%2C%20raising%20concerns%20about%20coral%20reef%20die-off.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEven%20one%20of%20the%20coldest%20places%20on%20Earth%20-%20Antarctica%20-%20is%20feeling%20the%20heat.%20Sea%20ice%20is%20currently%20at%20a%20record%20low%20in%20the%20Southern%20Hemisphere's%20winter%20-%20the%20time%20when%20ice%20should%20soon%20be%20reaching%20its%20maximum%20extent.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMeanwhile%2C%20record%20rainfall%20and%20floods%20have%20deluged%20South%20Korea%2C%20Japan%2C%20India%20and%20Pakistan.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BGlobal%20mean%20temperature%20(itself)%20doesn't%20kill%20anyone%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Friederike%20Otto%2C%20a%20scientist%20with%20the%20Grantham%20Institute%20for%20Climate%20Change%20in%20London.%20%26quot%3BBut%20a%20'hottest%20July%20ever'%20manifests%20in%20extreme%20weather%20events%20around%20the%20globe.%26quot%3B%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20planet%20is%20in%20the%20early%20stages%20of%20an%20El%20Nino%20event%2C%20borne%20of%20unusually%20warm%20waters%20in%20the%20eastern%20Pacific.%20El%20Nino%20typically%20delivers%20warmer%20temperatures%20around%20the%20world%2C%20doubling%20down%20on%20the%20warming%20driven%20by%20human-caused%20climate%20change%2C%20which%20scientists%20said%20this%20week%20had%20played%20an%20%26quot%3Babsolutely%20overwhelming%26quot%3B%20role%20in%20July's%20extreme%20heatwaves.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhile%20El%20Nino's%20impacts%20are%20expected%20to%20peak%20later%20this%20year%20and%20into%202024%2C%20it%20%26quot%3Bhas%20already%20started%20to%20help%20boost%20the%20temperatures%26quot%3B%2C%20said%20Haustein.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EScientists%20expect%202023%20or%202024%20will%20end%20up%20as%20the%20hottest%20year%20in%20the%20record%20books%2C%20surpassing%202016.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3E(Except%20for%20the%20headline%2C%20this%20story%20has%20not%20been%20edited%20by%20NDTV%20staff%20and%20is%20published%20from%20a%20syndicated%20feed.)%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1690467120000%2C%2